title: For Sale:  S&W Model 19-3 4" Nickel
postcontent:
I hate to do it, but up for sale is my S&W Model 19-3 4" in nickel finish.  Looking to fund some other hobbies at the moment.  I picked this up in a trade last year, and it's just too pretty for me to shoot, so guess what?  It's got to move out of the drawer and into the hands of somebody that'll appreciate it more than me.  Great condition.  I'm the 3rd owner as far as I know, previous owner did not shoot it much and said he had acquired it from an old neighbor that was a cop and had it in a safe most of its life.  The trigger and hammer must've been finished at some point, as I don't believe they ever came like that from factory.  Previous owner was not under impression this was ever refinished based on original owner.  The grips are Targets, assumedly off of a later model based on what others said here.  They look great with the piece, and have only the small crack where shown.  Timing is good.  Only minimal rotational play in cylinder as I've found on all my S&Ws.  Probably the sweetest trigger of any of my handguns.  4 K46 *** serial.

$550 FTF in IL.  FOID Required.  Beautiful piece that belongs in someone's collection that isn't afraid to breathe on it.  PM me with any questions.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 8 in rare .25 cal.
postcontent: My grandfather bought this gun in the early 1900's and used it for deer.  He gave it to me in 1972 and I used it for deer and wild pig.  Very accurate and reliable semi-auto.  It is the early .25 caliber which is rare as they went to .30 cal soon after they started production.  The rifle is fully operational and I even have 1/2 box of ammo that I'll throw in.  Not in show condition as it rattled around in a buckboard and shows its history.  But it has been well taken care of and will add character to your collection.  Or you can get a feel for what it was like to hunt with one of the old 'spring-poles' back in the day.  They were called that due to the fact that it basically has two barrels.  The interior barrel slides back as part of the ejection process when the gun is fired.  A fun gun to shoot and has a lot of history.  Several of the posse that got Bonnie and Clyde were carrying Model 8's.  Several old Remington hunting posters feature it as well.  A real piece of history at a good price.
